{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17635927","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17635927"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:21:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:21:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17547"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17547","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17547"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.24,0.14,0.48,0,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10237"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76196"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10237","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10237"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17547"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61700"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"42"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1418"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5898"},{"type":"tags","id":"9385"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23940"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23944"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76196","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76196"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a history of slowly progressive weakness in her lower limbs over the past few years. She reports difficulty with balance and frequent tripping. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. There is a family history of similar symptoms in her father. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Neurological examination reveals muscle wasting in the lower legs, high-arched feet, and reduced deep tendon reflexes. Cranial nerve examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following conditions is most likely being described?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Guillain-Barre syndrome","Peroneal neuropathy","Hereditary neuropathy","Diabetic neuropathy","Multiple sclerosis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis clinical presentation is consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Ehereditary neuropathy\u003C/strong\u003E, specifically Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease. It is heterogeneous disease, most clasically characterised by a slow course of progressive muscle weakness and atrophy, particularly in the distal limbs. The preservation of cranial nerves and the presence of a family history support this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGuillain-Barre syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents as an acute ascending paralysis, not a slowly progressive condition over years\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeroneal neuropathy\u003C/strong\u003E would present with foot drop and sensory changes in the distribution of the peroneal nerve, but it would not typically have a hereditary pattern or affect both lower limbs symmetrically\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiabetic neuropathy\u003C/strong\u003E is a common cause of peripheral neuropathy, presenting in a glove and stocking distribution, however is less likely in a young patient without a history of diabetes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMultiple sclerosis\u003C/strong\u003E is a central nervous system disorder that typically presents with episodes of neurological dysfunction affecting different parts of the nervous system, often with visual symptoms. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe combination of slowly progressive distal weakness, family history, and preserved cranial nerves strongly suggests hereditary neuropathy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease is a hereditary neuropathy with a slowly progressive course.","Cranial nerves are typically preserved in Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease.","Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease primarily affects the peripheral nerves, leading to muscle weakness and atrophy."],"references":["Eggermann K, Gess B, H\u00e4usler M, Weis J, Hahn A, Kurth I. Hereditary Neuropathies. Dtsch Arztebl Int. 2018 Feb 9;115(6):91-97. doi: 10.3238/arztebl.2018.0091. PMID: 29478438; PMCID: PMC5832893.","Pisciotta C, Shy ME. Hereditary neuropathy. Handb Clin Neurol. 2023;195:609-617. doi: 10.1016/B978-0-323-98818-6.00009-1. PMID: 37562889.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61700"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17547"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61700","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61700"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-02T11:56:25+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-02T11:56:55+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10237"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76196"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group"